FULL CRITICAL REVIEW\par
Six decades of the Hall\u8211?Petch effect \u8211? a survey\par
of grain-size strengthening studies on pure\par
metals\par
Z. C. Cordero, B. E. Knight and C. A. Schuh\u8727?\par
Re\u64257?ning a metal\u8217?s grain size can result in dramatic increases in strength, and the magnitude of this\par
strengthening increment can be estimated using the Hall\u8211?Petch equation. Since the Hall\u8211?Petch\par
equation was proposed, there have been many experimental studies supporting its applicability\par
to pure metals, intermetallics and multi-phase alloys. In this article, we gather the grain-size\par
strengthening data from the Hall\u8211?Petch studies on pure metals and use this aggregated data to\par
calculate best estimates of these metals\u8217? Hall\u8211?Petch parameters. We also use this aggregated\par
data to re-evaluate the various models developed to physically support the Hall\u8211?Petch scaling.\par
Keywords: Hall\u8211?Petch, Grain-size strengthening, Nanocrystalline metals, Dislocations\par
